World Acceptance Corp. Will Be The Next Victim Of The Serial Lender Killer Known As The CFPB - World Acceptance Corporation (NASDAQ:WRLD) | Seeking AlphaSign in / Join NowGO»World Acceptance Corp. Will Be The Next Victim Of The Serial Lender Killer Known As The CFPBSep. 9.15 | About: World Acceptance (WRLD) Overbet For Value Long/short equity, Deep Value, tech, long-term horizonSummaryWorld Acceptance's lenders are willing to forego profit potential because the odds of CFPB action against World Acceptance are high.Fines and restitution along with unfavorable rule changes to the installment loan industry are likely to cripple World Acceptance's prospects.The CFPB can do whatever it wants, and it wants to kill World Acceptance Corp.I have been following the World Acceptance (NASDAQ: WRLD) story for a few years. I have been long puts for the last few months. For the first few years of following this company, I had formed a generally positive view of the company's prospects. If I were to enter a position, I imagined I would be buying stock or calls. By any standard metric (P/E, EV/EBITDA, Price/FCF, etc.), the stock looked cheap. From FY2010 to FY2014, revenue, net profit and operating cash flow consistently ticked up. At the low valuations it received during that five year run, it looked too good to be true - and it was.
Whitney Tilson posted an interesting article making the short case for World Acceptance in September 2013. I thought his conclusion that CFPB (Consumer Financial Protection Bureau) action is likely seemed to not be backed by a substantial amount of evidence. Tilson is far from the first to make a short case against World Acceptance focused on what some would call the company's unsavory business practices. Citron Research posted a scathing article about the company in 2009 that was similar in tone to Tilson's 2013 article. I considered most of the alleged violations against World Acceptance as merely potentially ethically questionable at worst and possibly nothing at all.
In March 2014, World Acceptance received a CID from the CFPB. I still did not think that this meant the potential demise of World Acceptance could happen anytime soon. Even if World Acceptance's business practices (absurdly high interest rates, selling useless insurance products, deceptive marketing practices, etc.) are in fact illegal (and I don't think they are), government agencies that could levy an enormous fine against the company or force the company to change some of its profitable practices are slow to act. After all, government agencies are not exactly known to be quick and efficient. I would expect the CFPB to be even slower and less efficient than a typical government agency given the makeup of its employee base.

Everything changed in late June of 2015. World Acceptance filed an 8-K that outlined a change in its debt covenants. Banks rarely take actions that lower its potential profitability. It goes against a bank's basic instincts to do so unless it has very good reason to believe financial distress is in the borrower's near future. There was a great article posted on Seeking Alpha in early July discussing an appropriate valuation of World Acceptance under various scenarios. The two basic scenarios are:

The CFPB unleashes its wrath on the company. The CFPB issues huge fines, demands restitution and changes rules in a manner that the business shuts down as there is very little hope of generating any future profits.
The change in the debt covenants (along with potential CFPB action) will bring a slow death to the company as its capital base deteriorates. The article then presents a potential value of the company in this scenario.

The basic valuation approach is estimating a probability that each scenario plays out and estimating the price per share under each scenario. The estimated fair value of World Acceptance is: P(Scenario 1) * E(Price per Share in Scenario 1) + P(Scenario 2) * E(Price per Share in Scenario 2). That's simple enough. I now believe P(Scenario 1) is now much greater than 50% and E(Price per Share in Scenario 1) is very close to 0. I initiated a bearish position on World Acceptance shortly after the change in debt covenants was presented in an 8-K filing, and the stock has fallen quite a bit since then. I believe that the stock is nowhere near its bottom in the mid-30s.
The stated goal of the CFPB is to protect consumers against the financial sector. This agency is the brainchild of Elizabeth Warren, widely regarded as one of America's most anti-bank legislators. Throughout her career in Congress, she has consistently taken a position against any company resembling a bank.
Warren's appointment to lead the CFPB by President Obama was blocked by Congress. However, a close ally to Warren, Richard Cordray was eventually appointed as director of the CFPB in January 2012. In the capacity of director of the CFPB, Cordray seems to have the authority to serve as judge, jury and executioner in cases against companies involved with payday loans and installment loans. At this point, you might be asking what law World Acceptance has violated. I am asking that same question.

The interest rates and fees that World Acceptance charge are within the confines of state laws. Using the Rule of 78 to calculate interest is legal as long as the term of the loans is not more than five years. Selling insurance at a price significantly higher than what the product's fair market value is not illegal. Perhaps there are isolated incidents of predatory and illegal activity within World Acceptance, but I do not see evidence of significant clear misdeeds across the firm. Of course, what is considered predatory, deceptive and unfair is quite subjective.
The CFPB seems to be an exception to a system of government that was founded on the principle of checks and balances. The CFPB interprets laws quite liberally, and unsurprisingly, that interpretation seems to always go against lenders. The PHH Corporation is challenging the constitutionality of the CFPB. At least two other similar cases against the CFPB ended in decisions that sided with the anti-bank bureau. I believe it is highly likely that Cordray will lay down his interpretation of the law on World Acceptance. The CFPB will likely use some combination of fines, restitution to "victims" and rule changes that dictate how World Acceptance may operate. This is not a parking fine or a speeding ticket. The penalty will likely be big enough to send the equity value of World Acceptance to zero.
The question is no longer whether the CFPB will crush World Acceptance. The relevant question is when the CFPB will give its final ruling that serves as a death blow to World Acceptance. Given the possible change in the political environment in 2017 (when a new President takes over), I believe CFPB action will occur before then. This action will likely happen in late 2015. It is now a race between the CFPB and SEC to take down World Acceptance. However, I don't think the SEC investigation will materially impact World Acceptance as the CFPB is likely to kill World Acceptance on its own.
Almost 17 months passed between the day the CFPB issued a CID and the day it issued a NORA (Notice and Opportunity to Respond and Advise) letter to World Acceptance. Under normal circumstances, World Acceptance would have replied to the NORA letter within 2 weeks of receipt of it. That reply should have been sent out no later than August 21, 2015. Another 2 weeks have passed and the waiting game continues for the CFPB to act. It is almost inconceivable that World Acceptance could make an argument that could persuade the CFPB to believe its 17 month fact finding mission that resulted in the NORA letter missed important details that could dramatically sway the opinion of the CFPB.

The biggest concern I have for the short case for World Acceptance is the uncertainty in how long it will take before the CFPB acts. Government agencies tend to be inefficient, the CFPB probably more so than others, and that inefficiency is my biggest concern to the short thesis against World Acceptance as the possibility of the CFPB taking far longer than I expect to act is not immaterial. World Acceptance will likely not get fair treatment from the CFPB, and no one cares enough to intervene. For World Acceptance, the fate of its stock is likely a crash to zero.
Disclosure: I am/we are short WRLD. 
